fice of the Secretary and Deputy Secretary of Defense                                 12,171         9,754        14,265        4,511 Assistant Secretary of Defense for Legislative Affairs (ASD(LA))                                       549           308           768       460 Assistant Secretary of Defense for Special Operations/Low-Intensity Conflict (ASD(SO/LIC)) & -      8,790         9,042         252 Secretariat for Special Operations (SSO) Assistant to the Secretary of Defense, Privacy, Civil Liberties, and Transparency (ATSD/PCLT)     11,149         8,498         9,887        1,389 Assistant to the Secretary of Defense for Public Affairs (ATSD(PA))                                5,620         4,784         3,821         (963) Chief Digital and Artificial Intelligence Officer (CDAO)                                         315,586       329,894       131,628     (198,266) Defense Innovation Unit (DIU)                                                                             -     17,345               -    (17,345) Director, Administration and Management (DA&M)                                                    31,676        37,551        40,767        3,216 Director, Cost Assessment and Program Evaluation (D,CAPE)                                         38,498        38,472        28,373      (10,099) Director, Operational Test and Evaluation (D,OT&E)                                                 1,685         1,534         1,420         (114) DoD Chief Information Officer (DoD CIO)                                                          107,891        95,638        78,788      (16,850) Office of General Counsel (OGC)                                                                    4,535         3,680         3,984         304 Office of the Director of Net Assessment (ODNA)                                                   27,041        26,514        20,649       (5,865) Office of the Under Secretary of Defense for Acquisition and Sustainment (OUSD(A&S))             536,090       587,619       262,083     (325,536) Office of the Under Secretary of Defense Comptroller (OUSD(C))                                   132,085       131,992       138,652        6,660 Office of the Under Secretary for Intelligence and Security (OUSD(I&S))                          143,932       123,096       111,191      (11,905) Office of the Under Secretary for Personnel and Readiness (OUSD(P&R))                            159,233       137,835       106,586      (31,249) Office of the Under Secretary of Defense for Policy (OUSD(P))                                    118,176       143,285       186,539       43,254 Office of the Under Secretary of Defense for Research and Engineering (OUSD(R&E))                 96,844        82,118        15,114      (67,004) Strategic Capabilities Office (SCO)                                                                       -             -            -            - Test Resource Management Center (TRMC)                                                             3,231         3,079         3,039          (40) Corporate and other costs                                                                        376,026       410,317       304,300     (106,017) Total                                                                                           2,122,018     2,202,103     1,470,896    (731,207) OSD 733 OSD Offices/Principal Staff Assistants Mission Descriptions: Immediate Office of the Secretary and Deputy Secretary of Defense: Includes the SECDEF and DEPSECDEF as well as their support staff tasked with operating the Department. Assistant Secretary of Defense for Legislative Affairs (ASD(LA)): The ASD(LA) serves as the PSA and advisor to the SECDEF for DoD relationships with the U.S. Congress and oversees DoD legislative affairs. The ASD(LA) promotes the DoD defense budget and strategy, legislative priorities, and policies to the U.S. Congress. The ASD(LA) priorities support required contracts specializing in critical areas of research and operational requirements necessary to accomplish the LA mission as defined by the Department. Assistant Secretary of Defense for Special Operations/Low-Intensity Conflict (ASD(SO/LIC)) & Secretariat for Special Operations (SSO): The ASD(SO/LIC) serves as the PSA to the SECDEF for special operations, low-intensity conflict, and special operations-peculiar administrative matters, in accordance with section 922 of the National Defense Authorization Act (NDAA) for Fiscal Year (FY) 2017; section 902 of the NDAA for FY 2021; section 907(a)(2) of the NDAA for FY 2025 ; and sections 138(b)(2)(A) and 139b of Title 10, U.S. Code. The SSO within the office of ASD(SO/LIC) exercises authority, direction, and control over all special operations-peculiar administrative matters related to the organization, training, and equipping of special operations forces, following the administrative chain of command specified in Section 167(f) of Title 10. Its mission is to shape the future of joint special operations forces (SOF) by fostering partnerships and advancing strategic initiatives that ensure SOF remains optimally organized, trained, equipped, and resourced to address evolving global security challenges. The SSO is focused on the following priorities and functions: 1) Design the future SOF force: deliver analytically grounded recommendations on SOF size, structure, posture and capability mix to reestablish deterrence and ensure long-term alignment with strategic threats, missions, and priorities. 2) Maximize performance and resilience of SOF personnel: develop policy and guidance to restore the warrior ethos and ensure the recruitment, selection, development, and retention of a highly capable future force. 3) Ensure training and readiness meets future needs: evaluate and advocate for readiness standards, training pipelines, and infrastructure to ensure the force is prepared for evolving and dynamic operational requirements. 4) Align capability development to strategic priorities: provide policy direction and oversight for special operations-peculiar and irregular warfare capability development. Ensure capability investments are aligned to rebuilding military strength, advancing modernization goals, and delivering real operational value. Clear hurdles to prototyping, experimentation, and fielding. 5) Rapidly solves asymmetrical and ambiguous problems, in partnership with interagency and international entities, especially where irregular warfare is central. Prioritizes rapid development of irregular warfare capabilities if they are tied to irregular warfare missions; no other DoD entity is solving it at operational speed; and it can field something faster or more adaptable than formal acquisition programs. It ensures irregular warfare technology development is aligned with national policy as well as operational demand signals. 6) Strengthen resource oversight and institutionalize accountability: advance data-driven analysis and tools to enhance fiscal responsibility and ensure resourcing decisions are tracked and aligned to strategic outcomes across the SOF enterprise. SSO priorities and functions grounded in data, performance metrics, and rigorous analysis . The SSO also leverages technology to lead OSD 734 development of tools and frameworks that enable transparent, measurable oversight and implementation of the SSO initiatives across the organize-train-equip-resource spectrum. Assistant to the Secretary of Defense for Privacy, Civil Liberties, and Transparency (ATSD(PCLT)): The DoD is committed to executing its mission in a manner that fully respects and protects privacy and civil liberties while promoting increased transparency across the Department and with all external partners and stakeholders. Through policies, practices, training, and governance, ATSD(PCLT) spearhead’s DoD commitment to becoming the model for protecting privacy and civil liberties and promoting transparency. An integrated PCLT capability that crosses both intelligence and non-intelligence activities, including appropriate independent oversight, is critical to the Department's success. Current funding for the Office of the Assistant to the Secretary of Defense for Privacy, Civil Liberties, and Transparency (OATSD(PCLT)) will be used to support traditional mission requirements while simultaneously enabling OATSD(PCLT) to expand its capability to address DoD-wide challenges such as: 1) Governance and oversight of the acquisition and use of commercially available information; 2) Improved visibility into the identification, reporting, and remediation of loss or compromise to personally identifying information; 3) Reduction of DoD-wide FOIA backlog; 4) Coordinated independent oversight of intelligence, intelligence-related, and sensitive activities; and 5) Improved training of DoD personnel in the areas of privacy, civil liberties, FOIA, intelligence oversight, and the regulatory process, specifically relating to the application of emerging technologies in these areas. Assistant to the Secretary of Defense for Public Affairs (ATSD(PA)): Assistant to the Secretary of Defense for Public Affairs (ATSD(PA)): The ATSD(PA) serves as the PSA and advisor to the SECDEF and DEPSECDEF for DoD news media relations, internal communications, community outreach, public affairs, and audio-visual information. Adherent to SECDEF guidance, the ATSD(PA) is the sole authority for releasing official DoD information to news media representatives and providing Department information to the public, the Congress, and the media. The ATSD(PA) sponsors the DoD Defense.gov website, which is DoD's official website and the starting point for finding U.S. military information online. The ATSD(PA) is the principal spokesperson for the DoD and supports all SECDEF press briefings and responds to all public inquiries to the DoD. The ATSD(PA) funding supports specialized contracts pursuant to fulfillment of designated responsibilities, which include planning, analysis, non- inherently government functions required for government operations, information technology (IT) operations, administrative, scheduling, and support functions. Funding additionally supports specialized contracts producing the Defense Morning Clips, maintenance and hosting of official websites and information sharing capabilities as directed by the SECDEF’s guidance. Chief Digital and Artificial Intelligence Officer (CDAO): The CDAO’s mission is to accelerate DoD adoption of data, analytics, and artificial intelligence (AI) for decision advantage. There are two main goals of this mission: 1) deliver industry’s best data, analytics, and AI capability to joint decision makers at speed and scale to enable better, faster decisions and increase lethality and efficiency; and 2) remove systemic barriers to digital technology adoption so DoD innovation can occur with more agility, speed, and impact. The CDAO is responsible for strengthening and integrating data, analytics, AI and machine learning (AI/ML), and digital solutions for the Department. The CDAO team consists of data and AI OSD 735 experts, product managers, and bureaucratic process hackers to rapidly deliver digital capabilities and remove systemic barriers to more agile, data-driven ways of working. In FY 2026, the CDAO will continue striving to accelerate capability delivery, set the foundation for scale, and facilitate DoD adoption and agility. The CDAO will redouble focus for reducing time to award and increasing opportunity for non-traditional companies through Tradewinds and will accelerate trusted capability into the hands of warfighters and leverage our Nation’s competitive advantages in the tech sector. By investing in core infrastructure and services, we are streamlining industry access to DoD contracts, networks, data, and users. By removing barriers through governance, we are enabling repeatable enterprise and local innovation. The CDAO data resources are critical to maximizing the value data from the boardroom to the battlefield. The resources requested in this budget will enable the CDAO to provide enterprise data management (e.g., developing and issuing required data policies, guidelines, and processes), ensure implementation of the DoD Data Strategy, performance of data governance (e.g., leading DoD Data Council, supporting data issues in other DoD bodies, and engagement with industry, interagency, and international data leaders), and development of a data-enabled workforce in support of the INDSG and section 1513 of the NDAA for FY 2023. Additionally, the CDAO will also use these resources to continue working with PSAs to develop the data access, data quality, processes, and metrics needed to scale analytics at the enterprise level in support of section 1552 of the NDAA for FY 2023. The CDAO will sustain vital joint enterprise services and mission solutions, which includes expanding the enterprise data repository, establishing a responsible AI ecosystem, implementing the AI and Data Accelerator Initiative, and implementing the Data, Analytics, and AI Adoption Strategy. These various lines of effort will support the overarching mission of accelerating the Department's adoption of data, analytics, and AI to preserve decision advantage across the joint force. Defense Innovation Unit (DIU): The DIU mission is to strengthen U.S. national security by accelerating the adoption of commercial technology throughout the Department while growing the national security innovation community. The DIU partners with organizations across the Federal Government, DoD, intelligence community, and domestic and foreign partners to rapidly prototype, field, and scale commercially derived solutions to meet the most critical operational capability gaps identified by the Department with the focus, speed, and scale required to help deter major conflict and win if forced to fight. With offices in Silicon Valley, Boston, Austin, Chicago, and the Pentagon, DIU is able to attract the best and brightest talent and cutting-edge solutions. The DIU operating budget supports the organization’s role as a PSA and advisor to the SECDEF and DEPSECDEF and supports DoD’s initiatives to build enduring advantages across the defense ecosystem - the DoD, defense industrial base, and array of private sector enterprises and academia that create and sharpen the joint force’s technological edge, with a focus on innovation and rapid adjustment to new strategic demands. In addition to supporting core DIU functions, the requested funding supports operational requirements for IT, due diligence and business intelligence software licenses, travel, and administrative functions for the National Security Innovation Network and National Security Innovation Capital programs. OSD 736 The Performance Improvement Officer & Director of Administration and Management (PIO/DA&M): The PIO/DA&M is the Performance Improvement Officer of the DoD and the Director of Administration and Management. The PIO/DA&M has been designated by the SECDEF as the DoD PIO, Defense Reform Lead, and the PSA to the SECDEF and DEPSECDEF for organizational and management matters. The PIO/DA&M is responsible for the preparation of the Department’s Strategic Management Plan, assisting the SECDEF in ensuring the mission and goals of the Department are achieved through strategic and performance planning and the regular assessment of progress using executive analytics to improve results. The PIO/DA&M oversees the Pentagon Reservation, including all construction, renovation, facility operations, maintenance, and security; provides administrative, personnel, and budget support to the Office of the Secretary of Defense (OSD), select Defense Agencies, and DoD personnel assigned to the National Capital Region (NCR); and exercises the authority, direction, and control over the Directors of the Pentagon Force Protection Agency (PFPA) and Washington Headquarters Services (WHS). Key activities conducted in the Office of the PIO/DA&M include: • Representing the Department in the Office of Management and Budget’s Performance Improvement Council. • Overseeing Information Management and Technology for OSD. • Serving as both the senior official for Information Management and Technology and Chief Information Officer for OSD to manage the OSD IT Enterprise. • Overseeing and facilitating control, processing, and archiving of SECDEF, DEPSECDEF, and DoD Executive Secretary correspondence. • Providing support to senior governance venues (e.g., Deputy’s Workforce Council, Deputy’s Management Action Group (DMAG), Large Group, etc). • Chairing the Defense Performance Improvement Council, a supporting tier of governance for the DMAG. • Developing and implementing the Department’s Enterprise Risk Management Framework. • Coordinating matters pertaining to the accession and departure of key senior DoD personnel and serves as the DoD Transition Director (designated senior career official for transition, as required by statute). • Serving as DoD-wide liaison with the Government Accountability Office for high risk and audit recommendations’ management; supports the Office of the DoD Inspector General (IG) in follow-up activities for the IG Compendium; and Top Management Challenges. • Supporting the DEPSECDEF participation in the President’s Management Council. • Developing, managing, and implementing policies and procedures for the DoD Special Access Program. • Providing support to the Defense Business Board. • Serving as the DoD representative to the National Capital Planning Commission. • Representing the Department as the sponsor for the Defense Management Institute. • Supporting the Department’s compliance with Evidence Act Title I statutory requirements. OSD 737 Director, Cost Assessment and Program Evaluation (D,CAPE): The D,CAPE provides the SECDEF and other DoD senior leaders non- advocate, unbiased, and fact-based decision support on the size, shape, affordability, disposition, and readiness of the future joint force to achieve the INDSG. This includes analyzing the Defense Program by leading strategic portfolio reviews and the annual program review, supporting the acquisition process by providing senior acquisition executives with independent cost estimates as well as guidance and sufficiency reviews of Analyses of Alternatives and leading DoD’s analytic and cost communities. The D,CAPE funds analyses that inform cost estimating, long range planning, developing, and maintaining a database of actual operating and support costs for major weapons systems, requirements for strategic portfolio reviews, and developing the analytic community within DoD. Through studies and analyses, the D,CAPE offers tradeoffs and alternatives and assesses best practices and affordability options to modernize capabilities effectively to advance national strategy. These analyses are groundbreaking, comprehensive, and data-driven to explore capabilities that improve the force's lethality. Resources support key priorities such as: the Analysis Working Group, rebuilding military readiness, campaign analysis, force planning analysis, and reforming DoD business practices. Through competitive sourcing and consolidation, the D,CAPE continues to optimize spending on contracts and contract personnel supporting those efforts. Overall resources are balanced to support competing demands such as the modernization of the D,CAPE analytic and business IT systems, congressionally-mandated studies, SECDEF priorities, continuing strategic reviews, and strategic and warfighting analyses as prioritized by the DEPSECDEF and the Vice-Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff (VCJCS). The activities include: 1) Long Range Planning 2) Cost Estimating and Program Evaluation Economic Research 3) Strategic, C4, and ISR Programs 4) Conventional Forces Analytical Support 5) Readiness and Force Employment Analysis 6) Irregular Warfare, Mobility Capability, and Force Projection Analyses 7) Force Structure, Weapons Systems, and Warfighting Analysis 8) Support for Strategic Analysis and Campaign Analysis 9) Industrial Base Assessments 10) Enterprise Data Initiatives 11) Cost Data Support Group 12) Manpower Analysis 13) Modeling and Simulation 14) Programmatic and Budgetary Data Requirements 15) Enterprise Visibility and Management of Operating and Support Cost (EVAMOSC) OSD 738 Director, Operational Test and Evaluation (D,OT&E): Section 139 of Title 10, U.S. Code, requires the D,OT&E to prescribe policies and procedures for the conduct of operational test and evaluation in DoD. The D,OT&E monitors and reviews all operational tests to confirm operational effectiveness and suitability of the defense system in combat use. Additionally, the D,OT&E supports mission-essential headquarters travel and hosting of the D,OT&E public-facing website. DoD Chief Information Officer (DoD CIO): The DoD CIO is the PSA and advisor to SECDEF and DEPSECDEF for IT, including national security systems and information resources management (IRM) matters. The DoD CIO is responsible for all matters relating to the DoD information enterprise. The DoD CIO develops Department-wide strategy and policy on DoD IT and information systems. In direct support of the INDSG, DoD CIO develops and promulgates enterprise-wide architecture requirements, and technical, operational, protection and interoperability standards. Additionally, DoD CIO ensures interface continuity between DoD and non-DoD systems. The DoD CIO activities support the modernization and development of advanced IT capabilities which directly enhances resiliency by focusing attention on modernizing key information capabilities and ensuring that DoD maintains an advantage over adversaries in the areas of cybersecurity, information, and communications technology. The DoD information enterprise and systems resource management activities include: 1) command, control, and communication (C3), including positioning, navigation, and timing (PNT) policy and spectrum management; 2) E-Gov initiatives and government-wide councils; and 3) software modernization (development, security, operation), including cloud computing. Office of General Counsel (OGC): The OGC is headed by the DoD General Counsel. Appointed by the President with the advice and consent of the Senate, the General Counsel is, by law, the Chief Legal Officer of the DoD, in accordance with section 140 of Title 10, U.S. Code. The DoD General Counsel shares direct legal responsibilities and functions with the Defense Legal Services Agency (DLSA) and is responsible for, but not limited to, the following functional areas: •   Provides advice to the SECDEF and DEPSECDEF regarding all legal matters and services performed within, or involving, the DoD. •   Directs legal services performed within DoD, including determining the adherence of DoD attorneys to appropriate professional standards. •   Serves in two capacities: as DoD General Counsel and as the Director of DLSA, a DoD agency that provides legal advice and services for the Defense Agencies, DoD Field Activities, and other assigned organizations. Office of the Director Net Assessment (ODNA): The ODNA provides SECDEF, DEPSECDEF, DoD, Military Services, and CCMDs with comparative analyses of military, technological, and other factors affecting the military capability of the United States and other nations, with the goal of identifying emerging problems and opportunities that deserve the attention of senior defense officials. These analytical techniques are essential to diagnosing the most critical elements of short- and long-term strategic competition and understanding their implications, strategic risks, and opportunities. These techniques provide highly valued analytical insights to senior DoD leaders, drawing on expertise and resources not available within the DoD. This research differs in character and focus from other DoD research programs, which are concerned with issues of current or near future policy. OSD 739 Office of the Under Secretary of Defense for Acquisition and Sustainment (OUSD(A&S)): The OUSD(A&S) is the PSA and advisor to SECDEF and DEPSECDEF for all matters relating to acquisition and sustainment in DoD. The primary responsibilities of OUSD(A&S) include serving as DoD’ chief acquisition and sustainment officer with the mission of enabling the delivery and sustainment of secure and resilient capabilities to the warfighter and international partners quickly and cost effectively. The OUSD(A&S) is also responsible for establishing policies and supervising all elements of acquisition, sustainment, the defense industrial base, and modernization of the nuclear forces. The OUSD(A&S)'s major activities include Readiness and Environmental Protection Initiative (REPI), Logistics Systems Modernization (LSM) support, Native American Lands Environmental Mitigation Program (NALEMP), Global Investments and Economic Security (GIES), APEX Accelerators, and Chemical and Biological Weapons Elimination (CBWE) support program. Other OUSD(A&S) 's activities include: 1) Acquisition Program Support Systems 2) Acquisition Integration and Interoperability (AI2) 3) Acquisition Innovation 4) Acquisition Visibility 5) Contracting Enablers, Initiatives, and Pricing 6) Chief Financial Officer Act Compliance 7) Chemical Biological Weapons Program Support 8) Contracting E-Business Capabilities 9) Core Services 10) Cost Effective Material Readiness 11) Cyber Integration 12) Defense Installation Data Infrastructure (DISDI) 13) Defense Management Initiatives (DMI) 14) DoD Legacy Program 15) DoD Siting Clearinghouse 16) Emerging Contaminants 17) Energy Office 18) Environmental Safety and Occupational Health (ESOH) 19) Environmental Resiliency 20) FFRDC Oversight 21) Committee on Foreign Investment in the United States (CFIUS) 22) Human Capital Initiatives (HCI) OSD 740 23) Installation & Environment Business Enterprise Integration 24) Industrial Policy Program Support 25) Information and Integration Portfolio Management 26) International Cooperation Program Support 27) OUSD(A&S) Travel 28) Official Representation Funds 29) Policy, Analysis and Transition 30) Product Life-Cycle Sustainment 31) Quick Reaction Special Projects (QRSP) 32) Small Business Program Support 33) Threat Reduction and Arms Control Office of the Under Secretary of Defense (Comptroller) (OUSD(C)): The OUSD(C) is the PSA to the SECDEF for budgetary and fiscal matters, including financial management, accounting policy and systems, audit and audit remediation, management control systems, budget formulation and execution, and data analytics. The OUSD(C) is responsible for managing the review, formulation, presentation, and execution of the budget for the DoD. In doing so, the OUSD(C) works to achieve economy and efficiency in DoD operations through sound business judgment and effective fiscal planning and control. The OUSD(C) ensures DoD leaders have access to high quality, timely, and analyzed data for decision- making through a business framework that simplifies processes, standardizes systems and information, and promotes financial policies and internal controls. This framework supports effective and efficient financial management operations with a focus to achieve and sustain unmodified (or clean) audit opinions across the Department. In support of DoD’s financial management workforce, the OUSD(C) develops and sustains developmental programs including the DoD Financial Management Certification Program. The activities include: Comptroller initiatives, administrative support; and the Next Generation Resource Management System. Office of the Under Secretary for Intelligence and Security (OUSD(I&S)): The OUSD(I&S) is the PSA and advisor to the SECDEF and DEPSECDEF regarding intelligence, counterintelligence, security, law enforcement, sensitive activities, and other intelligence-related matters. The budget also supports OUSD(I&S)’s role in exercising the SECDEF’s authority, direction, and control over and oversight of the Defense Agencies and DoD Field Activities that are defense intelligence, counterintelligence, law enforcement, or security components and exercises planning, policy, and strategic oversight over all defense intelligence, counterintelligence, law enforcement, and security policy, plans and programs. In addition to the Military Intelligence Program (MIP) Management and Activities of the OUSD(I&S) operating budget, funding is provided for: • The Defense Military Deception Program Office, which provides governance, oversight, and operational implementation of military deception planning and execution capabilities across the DoD, including sensitive messaging, deception, influence, and other operations in the information environment. OSD 741 •   The OSD Red Team, which serves as the SECDEF’s and DEPSECDEF’s red team by providing insights on adversaries’ highest-level perspectives and potential actions to inform strategic-level DoD activities. The Red Team’s adversary-centric insights augment, complement, and are separate and distinct from other established channels of military advice or finished intelligence products and analysis provided to the SECDEF, DEPSECDEF, and the DoD components. The Red Team’s most valuable resource is its mix of operational and intelligence experts who bring distinct knowledge and skills not found elsewhere in DoD by providing exquisite insight to ensure adversary calculus and military responses are factored into deterrence and denial strategies. •   The Influence and Perception Management Office (IPMO), which is the OUSD(I&S) center of gravity for efforts to deliberately influence foreign defense and intelligence entities to behave in ways that benefit U.S. defense-related strategic interests. The IPMO integrates, matures, and operationalizes oversight, governance, and execution of cross-cutting influence activities. The IPMO’s activities include the development of thematic influence guidance and integrated influence strategies, oversight of intelligence support to operations in the information environment, oversight and governance of deception activities, oversight and governance of deliberate conceal and selective reveal of strategic defense capabilities, and management of designated compartmented programs. •   The Strategy Coordination Program Office (SCPO), which performs critical analyses and assessments for a variety of military, technical, and scientific programs, issues, and topics. The program coordinates among the Military Departments, CCMDs, and other U.S. Government departments and agencies, leveraging the whole-of-government enterprise through strategy coordination cells that provide tailored analyses, prioritized assessments, and recommended strategies to mitigate identified risks. •   The Counterproliferation of Weapons of Mass Destruction (CP/WMD) Office, which serves as the senior advisor to the USD(I&S) for understanding threats from biothreat/biotechnology and WMD. The office leads, coordinates, and integrates strategic defense intelligence initiatives to counter the proliferation of adversary biothreats and biotechnologies and WMD as well as the associated delivery systems and related technologies across the Defense Intelligence Enterprise. •   Advanced Intelligence Capabilities (AIC), which reports directly to the DEPSECDEF and the Principal Deputy Director of National Intelligence and synchronizes efforts across the Department and with other Federal departments and agencies to detect, identify, and attribute objects of interest in, on, or near military installations, operating areas, training areas, special-use airspace, and other areas of interest, and, as necessary, to mitigate any associated risks to the safety of operations and national security. This includes anomalous, unidentified space, airborne, submerged, and transmedium objects. •    The Law Enforcement Oversight and Compliance Directorate, which serves as the senior advisor to the USD(I&S) for law enforcement policy and provides oversight of the law enforcement community. The Directorate leads, coordinates, and integrates law enforcement initiatives to bolster standards and training of law enforcement officers, improve care and utilization of working dogs, strengthen the high-risk personnel program, and other related programs across the law enforcement community. Office of the Under Secretary for Personnel and Readiness (OUSD(P&R)): The OUSD(P&R) is the PSA and advisor to the SECDEF for: • Manpower and reserve affairs, including the recruitment and retention of both civilian and uniformed personnel • Reserve Component matters • Military family, childcare, spouse employment, and community matters • Provision and delivery of health care to the Force and the management and oversight of the Military Health System via oversight of OSD 742 the Defense Health Agency •   Force readiness issues, including operational and strategic readiness •   Education and training •   Safety and occupational health •   Suicide prevention •   Force resiliency •   Prevention of and response to problematic and violent behaviors, including sexual assault •   DoD Drug Demand Reduction Program •   DoD Dependent Schools via oversight of the Department of Defense Education Activity •   Commissaries and exchanges •   Non-appropriated fund activities, including Morale, Welfare, and Recreation activities •   Civil Military Programs, which include the National Guard Youth Challenge Program, STARBASE, and Innovative Readiness Training •   Resource allocation for interagency and intergovernmental activities, studies, special projects, and external requests that require DoD civilian and military personnel •   Collaboration with the Department of Veterans Affairs The OUSD(P&R) also oversees the preparedness of the Total Force to execute the INDSG, and National Military Strategy (NMS), to include the development of policies, plans, and tools for the reporting of readiness levels and analysis of the impacts of Department decisions on readiness; military education and training of Service members and units to execute assigned missions; and force safety and occupational health risk mitigation. The OUSD(P&R) mission is critical to advancing lethality and promoting meritocracy across the civilian and uniformed enterprises. The OUSD(P&R) is committed to ensuring a merit-based force, free of harmful diversity, equity, and inclusion influence and activities. The organization is leading the way toward cultivating a pipeline of strong civilian employees and uniformed personnel by investing in, building, and cultivating a talent pool with the requisite technical and leadership skills needed to drive results in functional areas, business units, and across DoD. This involves overseeing the Department’s personnel initiatives (e.g., Deferred Resignation Program and Voluntary Early Retirement Authority) to advance the President’s directives and SECDEF’s intent, optimizing the workforce in support of our core warfighting mission, and cultivating a more ready, lethal, and effective fighting force. Office of the Under Secretary of Defense for Policy (OUSD(P)): The OUSD(P) is the PSA and advisor to the SECDEF and DEPSECDEF on capabilities, force, and contingency plans necessary to implement the INDSG, defense policy, and the integration and oversight of DoD policy and plans to achieve national security objectives. The OUSD(P) represents the DoD to foreign governments, international organizations, and interagency functions. The OUSD(P) funding supports mission requirements to consistently provide responsive, forward-thinking, and insightful policy advice and support to the SECDEF and the DoD in alignment with national security objectives. OSD 743 OUSD(P) core mission areas include: Indo-Pacific Security Affairs (IPSA) - The ASD(IPSA) is the principal advisor to the USD(P) and SECDEF on international security strategy and policy on issues of DoD interest that relate to the nations and international organizations of the Asia-Pacific, its governments, and defense establishments and for oversight of security cooperation programs, including foreign military sales, in the region. Homeland Defense and Hemispheric Affairs (HDHA) - The mission of the OASD(HDHA) is to provide policy and planning oversight for DoD homeland defense and mission assurance, defense support of civil authorities, Arctic policy, and Western Hemisphere affairs matters. Advances and represents priority issues with U.S. interagency partners; U.S. Congress; allies and partners; U.S. state, local, territorial, and tribal governments; and private sector organizations. International Security Affairs (ISA) - The ASD(ISA) is the principal advisor to the USD(P) and the SECDEF on international security strategy and policy on issues of DoD interest that relate to the nations and international organizations of Europe (including the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO)), the Middle East, and Africa, their governments and defense establishments, and for oversight of security cooperation programs and foreign military sales programs in these regions. Space Policy (SP) - The ASD(SP) is the senior official responsible for the overall supervision of DoD policy for space warfighting under the authority, direction, and control of the USD(P). In addition, ASD(SP) is responsible for interagency coordination and international engagement on space policy and strategy. Cyber Policy (CP) - The ASD(CP) establishes and oversees the implementation of DoD cyberspace policy and strategy; integrates national cyberspace policy and guidance with DoD cyberspace policy and provides guidance and oversight on DoD cyberspace activities as they relate to foreign cyberspace threats, international cooperation, engagement with foreign partners and international organizations; and implementation of DoD cyberspace strategy and plans, including those related to cyberspace forces, capabilities, and their employment. Strategy, Plans, and Capabilities (SPC) - The ASD(SPC) serves as the principal civilian advisor to the USD(P) and SECDEF on national security and defense strategy and capabilities, force, and contingency plans necessary to implement the defense strategy. The ASD(SPC) is also responsible for policy management and advisory responsibilities for the following offices: Global Partnerships; Plans and Posture; Force Development and Emerging Capabilities; Strategy; and the Defense Security Cooperation Agency. OUSD(P) major program activities include: 1. OUSD(P) Operations 2. OUSD(P) Mission Support 3. U.S. Mission to NATO 4. Rewards Program 5. Office of the Principal Cyber Advisor OSD 744 6.   Ex Gratia Program 7.   Military Information Support Operations 8.   Anomalous Health Incidents 9.   Vietnam Dioxin Remediation Office of the Under Secretary of Defense for Research and Engineering (OUSD(R&E)): The OUSD(R&E) is the PSA and advisor to the SECDEF and DEPSECDEF for all matters relating to research and engineering and other related matters. The OUSD(R&E) serves as the DoD’s Chief Technical Officer and is responsible for unifying defense research, development, and prototyping activities across the enterprise. The OUSD(R&E) establishes policies on, and oversees, all defense research and engineering, technology development, technology transition, prototyping, experimentation, and development testing activities and programs. The OUSD(R&E) responsibilities also include: establishing a Department-wide, mission-focused roadmap for each of the critical technology areas strategies; developing and implementing a National Defense Science and Technology Strategy; leading the establishment and implementation of Department-wide protection methodologies that mitigate the risk of loss of critical technologies to determined adversaries; initiating critical prototypes within the OUSD(R&E) identified capability thrust priorities; developing policy and guidance for DoD Mission and Enterprise Architectures; establishing Open Architecture Standards, piloting alternate rapid acquisition approaches; and ensuring the integration of developmental and operational test and evaluation in coordination with DOT&E. The OUSD(R&E) activities include: 1) Defense Industrial Base Cyber Security 2) Developmental Test and Engineering 3) Mission Capabilities and Systems Engineering 4) Research, Development, Test, and Evaluation Oversight 5) Strategic Technology Protection and Exploitation Cyber Resiliency Initiative 6) Wargaming Incentive Fund 7) War Fighting Lab Incentive Fund 8) Office of Strategic Capital Strategic Capabilities Office (SCO): Established as a new PSA in FY 2025, the SCO mission is to develop and transition capabilities to counter near-peer adversaries in all phases of competition and conflict through leveraging near-term technologies and/or the unconventional use of existing programs to field disruptive capabilities that create new strategic effects (deterrence, power projection, cost imposition, surprise, and overmatch). SCO develops, demonstrates, and transitions operationally impactful capabilities to increase the lethality of the joint force in contested environments. The SCO serves as the senior advisor to the SECDEF and DEPSECDEF augmenting efforts within the Department with respect to strategic capabilities development and advise on the identification, analysis, and introduction of disruptive applications and new and OSD 745 unconventional uses of existing systems and near-term technologies, for both U.S. Government and commercial capabilities, to create operational strategic effects. Test Resource Management Center (TRMC): A field activity under the purview of the OUSD(R&E), TRMC ensures the Department has the necessary capabilities to test weapon systems that are currently in development. Mandated by Congress in the NDAA for FY 2003, TRMC governs and assesses the adequacy of DoD's Test and Evaluation (T&E) infrastructure to support the development, acquisition, fielding, and sustainment of defense systems; reviews and certifies proposed Service and Defense Agency T&E budgets for adequacy; and formulates and maintains a strategic plan for T&E resources to ensure they align to the INDSG. Capital Security Cost Sharing (CSCS): The CSCS supports DoD’s critical component of building relationships with other partners and allies and funds the DoD share of the Department of State CSCS and Maintenance Cost Sharing program as authorized by section 604 of the Secure Embassy Construction and Counterterrorism Act of 1999. The CSCS also funds the Department's share of the CSCS International Cooperative Administrative Support Services pass through. The CSCS funding supports more than 86,000 U.S. Government employees from more than 30 agencies at over 280 locations worldwide. Together with interagency contribution from the CSCS program and other reimbursements, the funding provides the necessary resources for New Embassy Compound (NEC) projects as well as site acquisitions at locations where NEC projects are planned in the future. Additionally, the request supports the maintenance, repair, and renovation of existing office and support (non-residential) facilities that are occupied by multiple agencies. These projects also address security deficiencies and include major security upgrades as part of the larger rehabilitation projects. The FY 2026 request includes $2,093,717 thousand of discretionary and $430,490 thousand of mandatory (reconciliation) for a total of $2,524,207. The mandatory request funds Deployable Test and Evaluation for All-Domain, Attritable Autonomous Systems (TRMC), Range/Test & Evaluation Improvements (DoD CIO), Golden Dome Cybersecurity (OUSD(A&S)), Office of Strategic Capital (OUSD(R&E)), and classified programs (DIU and OUSD(A&S)). Further information for this reconciliation request is provided in Sections 20002, 20003, 20004, and 20005 of the Reconciliation Exhibit. FY 2026 funding for homeland territorial integrity and security is included in Reconciliation Exhibit Section 20011: Homeland Border Security Initiatives. OSD 746$$, to_jsonb(ARRAY[]::text[]), to_jsonb(ARRAY[$${"fy24": 570971000, "fy26": 622821000, "name": "01. Compensation and Benefits", "fy25_current": 638922000, "fy25_request": 698922000, "fy25_cong_amt": -60000000, "fy25_cong_pct": -8.58}$$::jsonb, $${"fy24": 549000, "fy26": 768000, "name": "Affairs", "fy25_current": 308000, "fy25_request": 312000, "fy25_cong_amt": -4000, "fy25_cong_pct": -1.28}$$::jsonb, $${"fy24": 549000, "fy26": 768000, "name": "Operations", "fy25_current": 308000, "fy25_request": 312000, "fy25_cong_amt": -4000, "fy25_cong_pct": -1.28}$$::jsonb, $${"fy24": 0, "fy26": 9042000, "name": "Operations Low-Intensity Conflict", "fy25_current": 8790000, "fy25_request": 9533000, "fy25_cong_amt": -743000, "fy25_cong_pct": -7.79}$$::jsonb, $${"fy24": 0, "fy26": 9042000, "name": "Operations", "fy25_current": 8790000, "fy25_request": 9533000, "fy25_cong_amt": -743000, "fy25_cong_pct": -7.79}$$::jsonb, $${"fy24": 11149000, "fy26": 9887000, "name": "Privacy, Civil Liberties, and Transparency", "fy25_current": 8498000, "fy25_request": 8614000, "fy25_cong_amt": -116000, "fy25_cong_pct": -1.35}$$::jsonb, $${"fy24": 11149000, "fy26": 9887000, "name": "Operations", "fy25_current": 8498000, "fy25_request": 8614000, "fy25_cong_amt": -116000, "fy25_cong_pct": -1.35}$$::jsonb, $${"fy24": 5620000, "fy26": 3821000, "name": "Affairs", "fy25_current": 4784000, "fy25_request": 4850000, "fy25_cong_amt": -66000, "fy25_cong_pct": -1.36}$$::jsonb, $${"fy24": 5620000, "fy26": 3821000, "name": "Operations", "fy25_current": 4784000, "fy25_request": 4850000, "fy25_cong_amt": -66000, "fy25_cong_pct": -1.36}$$::jsonb, $${"fy24": 315586000, "fy26": 131628000, "name": "06. Chief Digital and Artificial Intelligence Officer", "fy25_current": 329894000, "fy25_request": 385576000, "fy25_cong_amt": -55682000, "fy25_